Multiply this by \( 4y - 4y^3 \): First, \( 4y \times (1 + 6y^2 + 35y^4) = 4y + 24y^3 + 140y^5 \). Then, \( -4y^3 \times (1 + 6y^2 + 35y^4) = -4y^3 - 24y^5 - 140y^7 \). Adding these together: \( 4y + 24y^3 + 140y^5 -4y^3 -24y^5 -140y^7 \). Up to \( y^5 \): \( 4y + (24y^3 -4y^3) + (140y^5 -24y^5) = 4y + 20y^3 + 116y^5 \). Therefore, the expansion of \( \tan(5x) \) as a power series in \( \tan x = y \) is approximately \( 4y + 20y^3 + 116y^5 + \cdots \). But the actual Taylor series of \( \tan(5x) \) is \( 5x + \frac{125}{3}x^3 + \frac{6250}{15}x^5 + \cdots \).
